<subSubSection id="C374657AC31CFF95FF419AAE5A3943A4" pageId="7" pageNumber="384" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BD136F1C31CFF95FF419AAE5F1440F8" blockId="7.[151,1436,402,681]" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C31CFF95FF419AAE5F2040A0" bold="true" box="[151,307,402,428]" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Distribution:</emphasis>
Western Amazonia in 
<collectingCountry id="F3797661C31CFF95FDE29AAE5C6840A0" box="[564,635,402,428]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3797661C31CFF95FD5E9AAF5CAD40A1" box="[648,702,403,429]" name="Peru" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Peru</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3797661C31CFF95FD1C9AAE5D3440A0" box="[714,807,402,428]" name="Ecuador" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F3797661C31CFF95FCB69AAE5DDD40A0" box="[864,974,402,428]" name="Colombia" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFFF4B00C31CFF95FC0B9AAE5B5340A0" author="Ribeiro-Junior, M. A. &amp; Amaral, S." box="[989,1344,402,428]" pageId="7" pageNumber="384" pagination="151 - 196" refId="ref18425" refString="Ribeiro-Junior, M. A. &amp; Amaral, S. (2017) Catalogue of distribution of lizards (Reptilia: Squamata) from the Brazilian Amazonia. IV. Alopoglossidae, Gymnophthalmidae. Zootaxa, 4269 (2), 151 - 196. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4269.2.1" type="journal article" year="2017">Ribeiro-Júnior &amp; Amaral 2017</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="F3797661C31CFF95FAA49AAE5EF640DC" name="Colombia" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Colombia</collectingCountry>
along the southern Amazonian region, in the departments of 
<collectingRegion id="49AAF813C31CFF95FC7B9A8B5A3240DD" box="[941,1057,439,465]" country="Colombia" name="Putumayo" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Putumayo</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49AAF813C31CFF95FBF99A8A5A9D40DC" box="[1071,1166,438,464]" country="Colombia" name="Caqueta" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Caquetá</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49AAF813C31CFF95FB4D9A8A5AFF40DC" box="[1179,1260,438,464]" country="Colombia" name="Vaupes" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Vaupés</collectingRegion>
and Amazonas (
<figureCitation id="13552A74C31CFF95FF769AE65EE940F8" box="[160,250,474,500]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1888,1912]" captionTargetBox="[217,1370,181,1864]" captionTargetId="figure-22@4.[217,1370,181,1864]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution maps for the cis-Andean microteiid lizards in Colombia (Alopoglossidae + Gymnophthalmidae). Circles are examined specimens, while squares are records from literature (see Supplementary Files for specific references). Red arrows indicate new records for Colombia. Black arrows show a zoom in to regions where several records overlap. The light green shadow indicates the Orinoco River basin, and the dark green the Amazon River basin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5681929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5681929/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD136F1C31CFF95FF119AC25A3943A4" blockId="7.[151,1436,402,681]" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C31CFF95FF119AC25F904314" bold="true" box="[199,387,510,536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Similar species:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C31CFF95FE5D9AC25C964314" baseAuthorityName="O'Shaughnessy" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[395,645,510,536]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Alopoglossus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="384" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="buckleyi">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C31CFF95FE5D9AC25C964314" box="[395,645,510,536]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">Alopoglossus buckleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be differentiated from other similar species due to the lack of occipital scales (present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C31CFF95FE78991F5C0C4330" baseAuthorityName="Werner" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[430,543,546,573]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Alopoglossus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="384" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C31CFF95FE78991F5C0C4330" box="[430,543,546,573]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">A. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C31CFF95FD81991F5D1F4330" box="[599,780,546,573]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Ptychoglossus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="384" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brevifrontalis">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C31CFF95FD81991F5D1F4330" box="[599,780,546,573]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">A. brevifrontalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); in having small granular scales on the sides of the neck, similar in shape to those near the tympanic aperture (non-granular, keeled and imbricated resembling those in the dorse in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C31CFF95FF2399575F8F4388" box="[245,412,618,645]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Alopoglossus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="384" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="avilapiresae">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C31CFF95FF2399575F8F4388" box="[245,412,618,645]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">A. avilapiresae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C31CFF95FE0799575C844388" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1885" box="[465,663,618,645]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Alopoglossus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="384" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carinicaudatus">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C31CFF95FE0799575C844388" box="[465,663,618,645]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">A. carinicaudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); and for possessing smooth ventral scales (strongly or weakly keeled in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C31CFF95FF6299B35F5B43A4" authorityName="Duellman" authorityYear="1973" box="[180,328,655,681]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Alopoglossus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="384" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="atriventris">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C31CFF95FF6299B35F5B43A4" box="[180,328,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">A. atriventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). For a more detailed description see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFF4B00C31CFF95FD3999B25A3543A4" author="Ribeiro-Junior, M. A. &amp; Choueri, R. &amp; Lobos, S. &amp; Venegas, P. &amp; Torres-Carvajal, O. &amp; Werneck, F." box="[751,1062,654,680]" pageId="7" pageNumber="384" pagination="227 - 270" refId="ref18483" refString="Ribeiro-Junior, M. A., Choueri, R., Lobos, S., Venegas, P., Torres-Carvajal, O. &amp; Werneck, F. (2020) Eight in one: morphological and molecular analyses reveal cryptic diversity in Amazonian alopoglossid lizards (Squamata: Gymnophthalmoidea). Zoological Journal of Linnean Society, 190 (1), 227 - 270. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / zoolinnean / zlz 155" type="journal article" year="2020">
Ribeiro-Júnior 
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C31CFF95FC4F99B35DC243A4" box="[921,977,654,680]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="384">et al.</emphasis>
(2020)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
